Reasoning: 

1. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - This paper primarily focuses on the design and implementation of a cellular network for vehicular communication, which falls under the scope of networking and internet architecture. 

2. cs.MA (Multi-Agent Systems) - The tinyLTE system is designed to be fully autonomous and multi-purpose, which involves the coordination of multiple agents (i.e., the eNB and EPC implementations). 

3. cs.RO (Robotics) - Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) are mentioned as a potential use case for the tinyLTE system, which falls under the scope of robotics. 

4. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) - The paper briefly mentions the security considerations for the tinyLTE system, such as the use of encryption and authentication mechanisms. 

5. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper includes a performance evaluation of the tinyLTE system, which involves analyzing the end-to-end latency and throughput of the network, which falls under the scope of information theory.
